<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-289-260  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 289 260.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  March 8 1990 n1204 p38(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How the host puts on a happy face. (technical problems of on-linedata service providers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jones, Keith.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Organizations that want to make data on host computers availableto external users, such as sales staff or clients, as well asinternal users face a number of technical problems.andP;  These includecontrolling external access to information that is being usedsimultaneously by internal staff and handling external users'command line devices on a system geared to synchronous, paged modeterminals used internally.andP;  The solution to these problemsimplemented by Jordan Information Systems is detailed.andP;  Access tothe firms data bases, stored on two IBM AS 400 hosts is providedto external users via a software package called Telecom Gold andan intelligent front-end interface running on 14 industry-standardmicrocomputers.andP;  A protocol converter box makes the front-endappear to the host as a collection of IBM 5252 series terminalslike those used by internal staff.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Jordan Information Services (information services).andO;Topic:     Information UtilitiesData BasesUser InterfaceOn-Line.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>